a Ago examines early modern attitudes toward possessions, asking what people did with their things, why they wrote about them, and how they passed objects on to their heirs. While some inhabitants of Rome were connoisseurs of the paintings, books, and curiosities that made the city famous, Ago shows that men and women of lesser means also filled their homes with a more modest array of goods. She also discovers the genealogies of certain categories of things—for instance, books went from being classed as luxury goods to a category all their own—and considers what that reveals about the early modern era. An animated investigation into the relationship between people and the things they buy, Gusto for Things paints an illuminating portrait of the meaning of objects in preindustrial Europe.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aArt objectszItalyzRomexHistoryy17th century. 0aMaterial culturezItalyzRomexHistoryy17th century. 0aWealthzItalyzRomexHistoryy17th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  a17th century, rome, europe, renaissance, thing theory, material culture, consumption, consumers, capitalism, account books, inventories, wills, inheritance, possessions, dispossession, consumerism, economics, nonfiction, history, connoisseurs, paintings, art, wealth, furniture, furnishings, clothing, collections, ostentatious, luxury, public display.1 aBouley, Bradford.1 aFindlen, Paula, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFindlen, Paula.1 aTazzara, Corey.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226008387423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226008387/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 200